The Cistern Gate

A woman sits on the lip of an old clan cistern with a walking staff across her knees. She's wrapped in dust-pale cloth that marks her as mesa folk, but there's something off about the way she holds herself, too still, watching you approach with the patience of someone who has been refused many times. A wooden cup rests beside her on the stone. The cistern is the only water for three hours in any direction.

"Guild mark," she says, nodding at your ring. "You'd be welcome at my sister's hearth. She married into the Redstone family before the rails came." She doesn't move the staff. "But the Redstones won't speak to me now. Say I bring ill fortune because I see things before they happen. Saw the census men coming, saw the tower going up on Shepherd's Bluff. All true, all unwelcome."

The sun hammers the back of your neck. Your water skin is three-quarters empty. She tilts her head, studying you with eyes that don't quite focus where you'd expect. "The Kesharat took the western spring last month. Clan law says this cistern is free water, but I've been keeping it. They'll take it too, soon enough. I've seen it. So I'm asking travelers for what they can spare. Payment for water they used to take freely." She lifts the cup. "Call it a toll. Call it theft. The water's still here, and you still need it."

choices:

* Move on = Not your concern
